import java.util.Scanner;

public class IfElseExample {
    public static void main(String[] args) {
        Scanner scanner = new Scanner(System.in);

        System.out.print("Enter your grade (0-100): ");
        int score = scanner.nextInt();

        if (score >= 90) {
            System.out.println("Grade: A — Excellent!");
        } else if (score >= 80) {
            System.out.println("Grade: B — Good job!");
        } else if (score >= 70) {
            System.out.println("Grade: C — Not bad!");
        } else if (score >= 60) {
            System.out.println("Grade: D — Need some work!");
        } else {
            System.out.println("Grade: F — Keep trying!");
        }

        // Switch statement
        System.out.print("Enter a day number (1-7): ");
        int day = scanner.nextInt();

        switch (day) {
            case 1:
                System.out.println("Monday");
                break;
            case 2:
                System.out.println("Tuesday");
                break;
            case 3:
                System.out.println("Wednesday");
                break;
            case 4:
                System.out.println("Thursday");
                break;
            case 5:
                System.out.println("Friday");
                break;
            case 6:
            case 7:
                System.out.println("Weekend!");
                break;
            default:
                System.out.println("Invalid day!");
        }

        scanner.close();
    }
}

phase1.explanation:
if/else controls which code runs based on conditions:

if (condition) {
    // runs if condition is true
} else if (anotherCondition) {
    // runs if first condition false, this one true
} else {
    // runs if all conditions false
}

Important: order matters! if (score >= 90) checked BEFORE if (score >= 80)

Switch statement: cleaner for checking multiple specific values:
• case value: — runs if expression matches
• break — exits the switch
• default — runs if no case matches

⚠️ Missing break causes fallthrough — the code continues to the next case!

