import java.util.Scanner;

public class IfElseExample {
    public static void main(String[] args) {
        Scanner scanner = new Scanner(System.in);

        System.out.print("Enter your grade (0-100): ");
        int score = scanner.nextInt();

        if (score >= 90) 
            System.out.println("Grade: A — Excellent!");
            System.out.println("You're a star!");  // Problem!
        else if (score >= 80) {
            System.out.println("Grade: B — Good job!");
        }
        scanner.close();
    }
}

phase2.explanation:
Without braces {}, only the FIRST statement belongs to the if block. The second println is NOT in the if block, so the else doesn't match any if statement!

Always use {} even for single statements — it prevents this error and makes the code clearer:

if (score >= 90) {
    System.out.println("Grade: A — Excellent!");
    System.out.println("You're a star!");
}

Rule: Use braces always. It's safer and more readable!

